analysis_text:
> DETAILS
This is a Marschak-Machina triangle. It represents all lotteries over three ordered outcomes as points inside a triangle, where the top corner corresponds to certainty of the best outcome and the right corner corresponds to certainty of the worst outcome. The position of a point reflects the probabilities assigned to these outcomes, with the probability of the remaining middle outcome determined implicitly so that all probabilities sum to one. Moving within the triangle changes probability mass across outcomes while keeping payoffs fixed, so the geometry represents probability tradeoffs rather than changes in outcomes. Indifference curves drawn over the triangle summarize preferences, with straight parallel lines characterizing expected utility and systematic curvature or fanning indicating violations of it.

The preferences shown in this triangle depart from straight, parallel indifference lines and instead exhibit a pronounced fanning-out pattern. When the probability of the worst outcome is near zero, the tradeoff between increasing the chance of the best outcome and adding downside risk is relatively mild, but this tradeoff becomes much steeper as the probability of the worst outcome rises. This indicates that downside risk receives increasing weight in evaluation, so maintaining indifference requires disproportionately large increases in the probability of the best outcome. Overall, the pattern reflects strong sensitivity to bad outcomes rather than constant expected-value tradeoffs.
tldr_text: Small chances of a bad outcome are acceptable, but as the chance of a bad outcome grows, a much larger chance of a good outcome is needed to make the gamble worthwhile.
